about six months.

752
00:50:03,923 --> 00:50:06,024
This time, a lot more people mailed in checks

753
00:50:06,344 --> 00:50:08,344
and they mailed out a lot more floppy disks.

754
00:50:10,605 --> 00:50:12,766
Well, now they were getting properly rich.

755
00:50:13,326 --> 00:50:16,808
It was around this time that the smiling men in suits

756
00:50:17,088 --> 00:50:19,529
started to swarm around as they do

757
00:50:19,729 --> 00:50:21,249
whenever a new industry is born,

758
00:50:21,309 --> 00:50:26,411
especially an industry led by artists and engineers

759
00:50:26,511 --> 00:50:28,832
and people that had no representation,

760
00:50:28,912 --> 00:50:32,393
no guilds, no unions, still today, sadly.

761
00:50:33,572 --> 00:50:40,114
So the smiling men in suits told my friends at id software that you know what that game needs to be in Walmart

762
00:50:41,454 --> 00:50:48,476
And they were right they put the game. They put doom 2 and Walmart and now there were truckloads of

763
00:50:48,536 --> 00:50:51,037
Cash being dropped off at my friend's doorstep

764
00:50:52,118 --> 00:50:58,400
But what they noticed was there were much bigger truckloads of cash being dropped off at their publisher GT

765
00:50:58,420 --> 00:51:00,520
Interactive's doorstep at that same time

766
00:51:01,646 --> 00:51:06,889
Which seemed odd, since these guys really were brand new to the games business.

767
00:51:07,929 --> 00:51:13,973
Their other products at the time were Richard Simmons' Deal O'Mill CD-ROM and Fabio's screensaver.

768
00:51:16,574 --> 00:51:17,235
I shit you not.

769
00:51:17,695 --> 00:51:20,917
And then they got Doom, and they went public for a billion dollars.

770
00:51:21,737 --> 00:51:26,420
And my friends at id Software were like, that seems odd.

771
00:51:26,540 --> 00:51:29,421
You know, we're doing pretty well for ourselves, but man, those guys that have...

772
00:51:30,533 --> 00:51:33,575
to just put the box in the stores really did well for themselves.

773
00:51:36,798 --> 00:51:38,499
They hired me after a while.

774
00:51:38,659 --> 00:51:41,141
There was a brief stop at this company called Duango, which

775
00:51:41,181 --> 00:51:44,103
was a way for people to play Doom from home against one another

776
00:51:45,164 --> 00:51:46,746
before you could do that on the internet.

777
00:51:47,666 --> 00:51:49,348
I'll skip over that one pretty quickly,

778
00:51:49,408 --> 00:51:51,369
but I did learn a couple of things at Duango.

779
00:51:51,689 --> 00:51:53,871
One was competitive gamers are nuts.

780
00:51:55,372 --> 00:51:57,474
Two was strip clubs are not really my thing.

781
00:51:59,098 --> 00:52:02,880
Important things to learn as you start your business travel in 1995.

782
00:52:04,261 --> 00:52:09,264
Luckily, my friends at id Software were impressed with the progress we had made at Duango

783
00:52:09,525 --> 00:52:16,529
with no experience in a brand new industry and people like myself outselling franchises.

784
00:52:17,810 --> 00:52:22,633
And they hired me at id and they explained to me that they weren't happy with their publisher.

785
00:52:22,693 --> 00:52:27,536
They were pretty sure they were getting much less money per unit than they should have.

786
00:52:28,445 --> 00:52:31,468
and they were pretty sure that these guys and their interactions with them

787
00:52:32,569 --> 00:52:36,772
you know were not the geniuses behind why their game was successful

788
00:52:38,273 --> 00:52:43,077
so they put me on a plane I came on as VP marketing and distribution at id Software

789
00:52:43,637 --> 00:52:46,439
they put me on a plane I put on my combat boots and I

790
00:52:47,120 --> 00:52:49,882
I tied my mullet back into a business ponytail

791
00:52:50,803 --> 00:52:53,925
and I went to New York City to go do battle

792
00:52:54,185 --> 00:52:57,528
with these mysterious kings of industry at GoodTimes Interactive

793
00:52:59,308 --> 00:52:59,588
Yep.

794
00:53:00,629 --> 00:53:05,911
And what I met there were some inspiring people.

795
00:53:06,512 --> 00:53:07,993
They were inspiring in the same way

796
00:53:08,033 --> 00:53:09,934
that I hope to be inspiring to you today,

797
00:53:09,954 --> 00:53:12,435
in that they were just not that impressive.

798
00:53:15,517 --> 00:53:17,358
Because look, if they had just been geniuses

799
00:53:17,418 --> 00:53:18,678
and a bunch of Ivy Leaguers,

800
00:53:18,999 --> 00:53:22,180
you know, and doing things that I could never do,

801
00:53:22,320 --> 00:53:25,722
I probably would have slunk home and tucked my tail

802
00:53:25,782 --> 00:53:27,623
and told my friends that their deal was fine.

803
00:53:28,546 --> 00:53:32,891
But I didn't, I didn't, because what I found there was a bunch of guys from the record industry

804
00:53:32,951 --> 00:53:36,715
and the toy industry that had no idea about video games or how they were made,

805
00:53:37,156 --> 00:53:38,137
did not really care.

806
00:53:38,578 --> 00:53:41,621
They just wanted that sweet, sweet cash, and lots of it.

807
00:53:41,961 --> 00:53:44,184
They also wanted to take credit for the work.

808
00:53:44,524 --> 00:53:45,965
that my friends had done.

809
00:53:46,666 --> 00:53:49,728
Luckily, my friends were some of the first to fight

810
00:53:50,249 --> 00:53:51,830
for their intellectual property rights,

811
00:53:52,350 --> 00:53:55,172
to put their name on the front of the box of the thing that they made.

812
00:53:55,493 --> 00:53:57,995
You know, things that seem obvious in retrospect,

813
00:53:58,155 --> 00:54:00,517
but were pretty against the grain at the time.

814
00:54:02,618 --> 00:54:05,581
So, I set about learning what these guys were doing.

815
00:54:06,902 --> 00:54:07,662
Here's the secret.

816
00:54:08,323 --> 00:54:09,143
It's not that hard.

817
00:54:10,497 --> 00:54:13,498
Publishing, sorry for anybody here that works in publishing,

818
00:54:13,578 --> 00:54:17,739
or marketing, or finance, but it's not that hard, guys.

819
00:54:18,559 --> 00:54:21,000
It's not that hard, certainly not compared to making a game,

820
00:54:21,100 --> 00:54:22,120
or making a hit game.

821
00:54:22,980 --> 00:54:26,361
So, I was like, these guys are, they hired a sales force,

822
00:54:26,401 --> 00:54:28,781
they hired a PR firm, they hired an ad agency,

823
00:54:28,822 --> 00:54:31,262
they hired manufacturing, and they hired distribution.

824
00:54:32,362 --> 00:54:33,983
I learned all of this in roughly a month.

825
00:54:36,109 --> 00:54:37,390
And I just hired the same people.

826
00:54:37,710 --> 00:54:39,531
I just hired the same companies they did.

827
00:54:40,331 --> 00:54:42,872
And I went back and I told my friends.

828
00:54:42,892 --> 00:54:45,734
I was like, okay, well, good news, bad news.

829
00:54:46,034 --> 00:54:49,776
Good news is we can publish your next game, Quake,

830
00:54:50,256 --> 00:54:50,696
ourselves.

831
00:54:51,457 --> 00:54:51,917
We can do it.

832
00:54:52,357 --> 00:54:54,058
I've got all the same people lined up.

833
00:54:54,798 --> 00:54:56,839
The bad news is you were absolutely right

834
00:54:56,879 --> 00:54:59,220
and these people were taking roughly four times more

835
00:54:59,421 --> 00:55:01,241
per unit than they should have been taking,

836
00:55:02,262 --> 00:55:03,983
which did not make my friends very happy.

837
00:55:05,510 --> 00:55:10,172
We did, luckily it took a year longer than we thought to get Quake out the door,

838
00:55:10,292 --> 00:55:13,134
and so I had some time to actually learn what I was doing.

839
00:55:13,994 --> 00:55:19,438
And we shipped Quake shareware ourselves, we got it distributed nationwide,

840
00:55:19,518 --> 00:55:24,220
just like the big bad guys in New York with all their Fabio screensaver prowess.

841
00:55:26,016 --> 00:55:29,658
And we did well enough to be able to renegotiate our deal

842
00:55:29,698 --> 00:55:34,981
with GT Interactive to what was more than three times what

843
00:55:35,241 --> 00:55:36,962
they had been making off Doom II.

844
00:55:37,342 --> 00:55:38,363
So I had done my job.

845
00:55:39,804 --> 00:55:42,345
id Software at that time did not want to become a publisher.

846
00:55:42,425 --> 00:55:43,846
They were pretty good at making games.

847
00:55:43,886 --> 00:55:45,247
They wanted to keep making games.

848
00:55:45,867 --> 00:55:51,711
So I left there and went on to Ion Storm with John Romero,

849
00:55:51,771 --> 00:55:54,992
which was another meant to be a powerhouse developer.

850
00:55:55,803 --> 00:55:58,625
I'm going to skip over that one because it was only a year of my life,

851
00:55:58,725 --> 00:56:01,646
but I did learn a couple of important things there.

852
00:56:02,267 --> 00:56:07,009
I learned how disastrous the idea of what we all thought was cool

853
00:56:07,509 --> 00:56:08,590
could be in this industry.

854
00:56:08,610 --> 00:56:11,771
Because we really, we were, you know, I was 26.

855
00:56:12,251 --> 00:56:16,153
I was the CEO of this new company in the top of a skyscraper in Dallas.

856
00:56:16,694 --> 00:56:19,235
We all had our 90s hair and our combat boots

857
00:56:19,455 --> 00:56:21,336
and our attitudes and our arrogance,

858
00:56:21,936 --> 00:56:23,037
and it was gross.

859
00:56:24,137 --> 00:56:24,638
It was gross.

860
00:56:26,366 --> 00:56:30,850
But I'm so glad I went there and I'm glad I experienced the full effects of what some

861
00:56:30,950 --> 00:56:35,894
ego can do to some bright and hard-working young game developers.

862
00:56:36,735 --> 00:56:43,101
Because I also met a guy named Doug Myers there, who I have a son named after now, and

863
00:56:43,201 --> 00:56:44,462
he was the opposite of that.

864
00:56:45,102 --> 00:56:49,987
He really redefined what cool was in my head and what success looked like.

865
00:56:50,765 --> 00:56:53,467
And it wasn't that he preached anything, he just demonstrated it.

866
00:56:53,788 --> 00:56:57,931
He was so kind, just naturally so kind and humble and present

867
00:56:58,511 --> 00:57:03,275
and made everyone that he interacted with, whether it was for days or weeks or 10 seconds,

868
00:57:03,435 --> 00:57:05,556
feel seen and appreciated.

869
00:57:06,497 --> 00:57:09,739
And sadly he passed away at a very young age,

870
00:57:10,840 --> 00:57:15,824
not too long after that, but definitely not just me but my partners that formed.

871
00:57:16,658 --> 00:57:22,263
God Games Gathering of Developers, after that, it informed all of us of sort of the goal,

872
00:57:22,603 --> 00:57:23,644
what we were trying to get to.

873
00:57:25,385 --> 00:57:29,769
God Games Gathering of Developers was a holy crusade for the artist side of the industry

874
00:57:29,889 --> 00:57:34,453
against these evil bastard publishers that we had struck out against.

875
00:57:34,974 --> 00:57:40,919
I had now negotiated deals, renegotiated with GT Interactive, moved it over to Activision,

876
00:57:40,959 --> 00:57:41,980
renegotiated there.

877
00:57:42,552 --> 00:57:46,835
and then negotiated the most lucrative deal in history for Ion Storm

878
00:57:46,915 --> 00:57:48,976
with really nothing to show for it.

879
00:57:49,596 --> 00:57:51,218
So I knew how far we could go

880
00:57:51,278 --> 00:57:53,879
and I knew how much money there was on that other side of things.

881
00:57:53,939 --> 00:57:56,221
And I was like, well, here we go.

882
00:57:56,781 --> 00:57:58,623
What if we band a few studios together?

883
00:57:59,603 --> 00:58:02,926
Because most of these publishers only had one or two hits at the time anyway,

884
00:58:03,026 --> 00:58:04,747
so we're like, we can make those.

885
00:58:05,710 --> 00:58:11,074
And so we formed Gathering of Developers, which was sort of like a United Artists or Image Comics.

886
00:58:12,074 --> 00:58:15,096
It was artists first, staking our claim in the industry,

887
00:58:15,576 --> 00:58:20,199
putting out to the world what it meant to get a good deal from a publisher.

888
00:58:21,140 --> 00:58:23,941
And we just made a lot of noise, pissed a lot of people off.

889
00:58:25,622 --> 00:58:26,383
And honestly, like...

890
00:58:27,810 --> 00:58:32,234
Yes, we wanted to be respectful to artists and we wanted to give them their intellectual property rights.

891
00:58:32,254 --> 00:58:37,417
We wanted to pay them fairly and we wanted to make sure they were always credited above us.

892
00:58:37,497 --> 00:58:40,339
But it wasn't just because we were nice guys.

893
00:58:40,459 --> 00:58:44,382
It was literally, that was the giant hole in the industry.

894
00:58:44,923 --> 00:58:48,125
If any of the other publishers had been doing that, there would have been no need for us.

895
00:58:48,485 --> 00:58:51,988
So, I thank you, 90s video game publishers.

896
00:58:52,708 --> 00:58:57,311
I truly feel like I stand on the shoulders of shitheads.

897
00:59:06,518 --> 00:59:09,019
God games like Image Comics and United Artists,

898
00:59:11,340 --> 00:59:16,023
well, we ended up selling out to the same evil bastards we struck out against.

899
00:59:17,044 --> 00:59:22,267
What I did learn there was about sociotopy being real and about those

900
00:59:22,307 --> 00:59:24,688
ideas that we typically associate with business,

901
00:59:25,069 --> 00:59:28,110
you know, the idea of a shrewd business person,

902
00:59:29,771 --> 00:59:34,034
just meaning that they're going to take advantage of you as quickly as possible.

903
00:59:35,560 --> 00:59:38,642
you know, the reason that most young people don't want to be a business person.

904
00:59:38,662 --> 00:59:41,643
It's really hard to identify

905
00:59:42,063 --> 00:59:44,744
heroes as business people. So,

906
00:59:46,605 --> 00:59:47,045
here we were.

907
00:59:49,202 --> 00:59:55,503
having fought this crusade on behalf of these developers that left Microsoft and EA and Activision and GT

908
00:59:55,923 --> 00:59:59,964
to join us, risking their next projects with us, taking a stand.

909
01:00:00,684 --> 01:00:09,486
And there I was, my partners and I being completely taken advantage of by some proper sharks in New York.

910
01:00:09,786 --> 01:00:14,027
By the way, all of these companies that I'm naming here out loud and talking shit about,

911
01:00:14,207 --> 01:00:15,947
I'm sure they're all wonderful people now.

912
01:00:17,073 --> 01:00:18,073
This was the 90s.

913
01:00:18,474 --> 01:00:19,214
Things were different.

914
01:00:20,214 --> 01:00:20,775
I had hair.

915
01:00:23,056 --> 01:00:25,677
Anyway, we sold the company.

916
01:00:25,957 --> 01:00:29,099
And I can tell you without hyperbole,

917
01:00:29,199 --> 01:00:32,320
when I signed that deal, it felt like I was

918
01:00:32,360 --> 01:00:33,821
signing my own suicide note.

919
01:00:36,062 --> 01:00:38,923
It went pretty well as suicides go.

920
01:00:40,364 --> 01:00:41,325
We all made some money.

921
01:00:41,385 --> 01:00:42,625
The developers made some money.

922
01:00:44,619 --> 01:00:49,104
Unfortunately, my friend Doug that I talked about died on the day that we could cash out,

923
01:00:49,164 --> 01:00:50,866
really robbing us of any joy there.

924
01:00:51,487 --> 01:00:56,132
But we had accomplished quite a bit, and we had proven that we could do it.

925
01:00:56,632 --> 01:00:59,395
And maybe we would catch our breath one day and do it again.

926
01:01:00,777 --> 01:01:02,018
Cut to a few years later.

927
01:01:02,038 --> 01:01:03,860
I had taken a break from games.

928
01:01:05,782 --> 01:01:08,384
I actually went back to work at Take Two, which was really fun,

929
01:01:08,404 --> 01:01:11,165
because I left in a blaze of glory,

930
01:01:11,385 --> 01:01:13,366
as you might imagine from my speech today.

931
01:01:14,247 --> 01:01:16,768
And I got to learn just how well we had done,

932
01:01:16,908 --> 01:01:20,770
how well it worked to treat artists with respect,

933
01:01:20,790 --> 01:01:22,471
to ship games when they were finished,

934
01:01:22,671 --> 01:01:24,913
when the artists told us they were finished,

935
01:01:25,473 --> 01:01:28,315
to let the artists have sign off on all the PR and marketing,

936
01:01:28,915 --> 01:01:31,436
to let the game developers choose our games.

937
01:01:31,816 --> 01:01:34,598
We had eight new million unit selling franchises

938
01:01:36,272 --> 01:01:39,415
18 months, two years we existed before Take-Two bought us.

939
01:01:40,175 --> 01:01:42,057
So I get to learn all that from the inside,

940
01:01:42,757 --> 01:01:44,299
got out of there as quickly as I could,

941
01:01:44,959 --> 01:01:48,382
and then, you know, I did what every group does

942
01:01:48,402 --> 01:01:50,243
that has a good run in their 20s,

943
01:01:50,323 --> 01:01:52,185
we put the band back together in our 30s.

944
01:01:52,305 --> 01:01:55,207
It's called Gamecock Media Group.

945
01:01:57,569 --> 01:02:01,533
Same principles, except our brand, our sense of humor,

946
01:02:01,613 --> 01:02:03,654
was very much about me at the time.

947
01:02:04,755 --> 01:02:05,476
And I was angry.

948
01:02:06,187 --> 01:02:08,067
I was hurt from what happened at God Games.

949
01:02:08,107 --> 01:02:09,427
I was angry at the industry.

950
01:02:09,467 --> 01:02:10,868
I was angry that everything was getting,

951
01:02:11,028 --> 01:02:13,969
this rush to get bigger and be taken more seriously.

952
01:02:15,269 --> 01:02:17,470
Something in me wasn't, it didn't sit right.

953
01:02:19,190 --> 01:02:21,871
Suffice to say, midlife crises are real.

954
01:02:23,451 --> 01:02:24,172
I had mine then.

955
01:02:25,889 --> 01:02:28,891
And then we had an economic collapse crisis on top of it

956
01:02:28,952 --> 01:02:33,855
I recommend doing both of those at the same time by the way if you're planning your midlife crisis

957
01:02:33,915 --> 01:02:38,057
Go ahead and do it on top of economic collapse. It works out better for everybody

958
01:02:39,458 --> 01:02:41,160
But at Gamecock Media Group

959
01:02:42,340 --> 01:02:49,205
While our sense of humor was sort of bullish and like you're all so dumb. We're so cool

960
01:02:50,826 --> 01:02:53,588
I met this guy I hired this guy named Nigel Lowry

961
01:02:54,819 --> 01:03:00,665
Nigel Lowry we rescued from an ad agency and he wanted to work in the game industry so

962
01:03:00,725 --> 01:03:05,771
badly that he wrote us a letter about it and he said, you know, I want this from the bottom

963
01:03:05,831 --> 01:03:06,452
of my peepee.

964
01:03:10,402 --> 01:03:10,923
That was enough.

965
01:03:11,644 --> 01:03:12,444
We got the job.

966
01:03:12,465 --> 01:03:18,591
And out of the ashes of that company, after the economy collapsed and our billionaires

967
01:03:18,671 --> 01:03:22,635
panicked and pulled out our investment, Devolver was born.

968
01:03:23,536 --> 01:03:28,842
With just a few of us piecing together what money we had left, doing one game at a time.

969
01:03:29,744 --> 01:03:32,665
making it absolutely not about me.

970
01:03:34,485 --> 01:03:35,266
Big lesson there.

971
01:03:35,286 --> 01:03:37,806
It wasn't about anybody.

972
01:03:37,846 --> 01:03:41,588
In fact, we had a fictitious company spokesperson

973
01:03:41,648 --> 01:03:42,868
because we were so insistent

974
01:03:43,308 --> 01:03:44,989
that this didn't become about me

975
01:03:45,109 --> 01:03:46,509
or about anyone in the company.

976
01:03:46,889 --> 01:03:49,330
It was about this mission and this way of doing work.

977
01:03:50,270 --> 01:03:52,591
And luckily, we caught quite a tailwind

978
01:03:52,711 --> 01:03:53,971
with the new wave of indies

979
01:03:54,271 --> 01:03:55,732
that cropped up around that time.

980
01:03:56,612 --> 01:03:58,813
And we had a great run for the last 12 years.

981
01:04:02,033 --> 01:04:04,895
This is all the things people were saying about us.

982
01:04:08,478 --> 01:04:11,780
Punk rock label, Death Row Records, Sub Pop,

983
01:04:12,260 --> 01:04:14,121
basically everything but a game company.

984
01:04:15,102 --> 01:04:17,283
And then recently, somebody called us,

985
01:04:17,463 --> 01:04:19,805
just last week, the HBO of video games.

986
01:04:21,086 --> 01:04:22,066
Amazing, we did it.

987
01:04:24,264 --> 01:04:28,505
So to pull this back a bit, I learned on the way here

988
01:04:28,585 --> 01:04:30,226
that this talk is supposed to be about how

989
01:04:30,266 --> 01:04:31,566
we adjusted to the pandemic.

990
01:04:32,646 --> 01:04:34,947
Devolver was already working virtually

991
01:04:35,607 --> 01:04:36,847
from the time we had a company.

992
01:04:37,448 --> 01:04:40,608
We were already actively supporting one another,

993
01:04:40,829 --> 01:04:41,909
checking in on each other.

994
01:04:41,929 --> 01:04:46,310
We had a sort of innate concern about the well-being

995
01:04:46,350 --> 01:04:47,130
of our developers.

996
01:04:48,290 --> 01:04:51,231
But it wasn't enough, because while we were having

997
01:04:51,271 --> 01:04:52,152
that incredible run.

998
01:04:53,369 --> 01:04:56,111
and working with all these tiny teams, one or two people,

999
01:04:56,171 --> 01:04:58,153
that made games like Hotline Miami,

1000
01:04:58,213 --> 01:05:00,275
or Enter the Gungeon with three people,

1001
01:05:00,375 --> 01:05:02,316
or Reigns with one, you know.

1002
01:05:03,157 --> 01:05:08,722
I found out, I had learned about depression personally

1003
01:05:08,902 --> 01:05:10,303
after losing my friend Doug,

1004
01:05:10,623 --> 01:05:12,485
and losing God Games back in the day.

1005
01:05:13,066 --> 01:05:14,787
And I had, you know, I had been to the depths

1006
01:05:14,847 --> 01:05:18,250
to where some pills probably saved my life in that moment.

1007
01:05:19,299 --> 01:05:23,201
And so, ever since then, I had a concern and a heightened awareness

1008
01:05:23,281 --> 01:05:26,202
of mental health issues in my own family, in my community,

1009
01:05:26,662 --> 01:05:27,843
and just how common it was.

1010
01:05:29,304 --> 01:05:31,265
In fact, I ended up losing my sister.

1011
01:05:31,765 --> 01:05:35,227
Her name was Dr. Lisa Michelle Wilson, PhD.

1012
01:05:35,867 --> 01:05:37,348
She was a doctor of psychology,

1013
01:05:37,848 --> 01:05:40,870
and she lived with crippling depression most of her life,

1014
01:05:40,970 --> 01:05:43,911
and eventually decided to leave us.

1015
01:05:45,558 --> 01:05:49,722
Suffice to say, mental health is first and foremost on my mind since then,

1016
01:05:50,162 --> 01:05:55,026
and I came to know that several of our star developers,

1017
01:05:55,587 --> 01:05:58,309
including some of the ones I just mentioned that made those hits for us,

1018
01:05:59,110 --> 01:06:04,614
had become so distressed while making their game, or shortly thereafter,

1019
01:06:05,034 --> 01:06:11,480
that four of them, within six months, individual stories had become institutionalized.

1020
01:06:12,447 --> 01:06:19,111
Like not just I need medicine, but literally working on their game from inside a mental health institution.

1021
01:06:20,832 --> 01:06:26,235
So that's when I was just like, this ride started to mean a little bit less to me.

1022
01:06:26,575 --> 01:06:31,778
And it wasn't because I didn't love the Devolver family, they're the absolute best

1023
01:06:31,858 --> 01:06:35,781
and nothing I ever do will be as fun as working with those guys.

1024
01:06:35,941 --> 01:06:39,763
Nigel, the guy I mentioned before, really took the mission of what we were doing.

1025
01:06:40,932 --> 01:06:45,415
a much kinder, more self-effacing sense of humor.

1026
01:06:45,435 --> 01:06:48,578
And we had fun with the industry,

1027
01:06:48,598 --> 01:06:51,000
but it was really having fun with ourselves

1028
01:06:51,280 --> 01:06:53,842
and then making sure our developers

1029
01:06:53,902 --> 01:06:55,383
were getting rich and famous.

1030
01:06:56,824 --> 01:06:58,005
But it wasn't enough anymore.

1031
01:06:59,086 --> 01:07:02,068
And so while Devolver didn't really make any big changes

1032
01:07:02,108 --> 01:07:04,710
during the pandemic, other than we couldn't tour anymore

1033
01:07:05,010 --> 01:07:07,392
and started to really, that's when we would get together

1034
01:07:07,432 --> 01:07:08,633
is all the shows we would do.

1035
01:07:09,950 --> 01:07:15,954
We really started to feel the isolation and I personally was well aware that

1036
01:07:16,514 --> 01:07:20,716
not only was Devolver not about me but it really didn't need me anymore if it ever did.

1037
01:07:20,816 --> 01:07:25,359
Like the brand was built, the vibe was built, the games were working, the team was in place.

1038
01:07:27,020 --> 01:07:29,261
And while it's not about me and...

1039
01:07:30,995 --> 01:07:32,577
something has to be about me, right?

1040
01:07:33,037 --> 01:07:36,259
When you're isolated and working from home

1041
01:07:36,479 --> 01:07:37,440
and not seeing your people,

1042
01:07:37,480 --> 01:07:39,221
you start to ask some different questions.

1043
01:07:40,362 --> 01:07:42,523
Especially I was starting to see my adult daughters

1044
01:07:42,584 --> 01:07:44,785
have some mental health struggles as well.

1045
01:07:46,006 --> 01:07:49,448
So this led me to my personal adjustment,

1046
01:07:49,709 --> 01:07:52,470
my personal recalibration during the pandemic,

1047
01:07:53,071 --> 01:07:56,193
which was a series of events

1048
01:07:56,333 --> 01:08:00,216
that led me to announce the company I announced last week.

1049
01:08:00,737 --> 01:08:03,678
It's called Deep Well Digital Therapeutics.

1050
01:08:04,659 --> 01:08:06,380
And this one's also not about me.

1051
01:08:07,240 --> 01:08:11,963
This is a group of, I think we're up to 47 or so now,

1052
01:08:12,583 --> 01:08:17,145
game developers, psychologists, neuroscientists,

1053
01:08:18,406 --> 01:08:21,348
clinicians, regulatory professionals.

1054
01:08:22,849 --> 01:08:27,530
huge group of people that have been volunteering their time for the last three to

1055
01:08:28,030 --> 01:08:31,051
15 months in service of defining a way

1056
01:08:33,231 --> 01:08:34,472
where we can medicinalize

1057
01:08:34,952 --> 01:08:39,473
games. And I'm not talking about gamification or edutainment, I'm talking

1058
01:08:39,533 --> 01:08:43,513
about putting rails and understanding and information in your hands about how

1059
01:08:43,593 --> 01:08:45,694
games are already quite therapeutic for people

1060
01:08:46,154 --> 01:08:49,975
and how a lot of people are already using them to sort of self-medicate in

1061
01:08:50,035 --> 01:08:50,835
times of crisis.

1062
01:08:53,380 --> 01:08:59,324
I won't go too far into that, but that's what I'm doing with my time because, you know,

1063
01:08:59,384 --> 01:09:05,368
while it's not about me, what is about me and what is about all of you regardless of

1064
01:09:05,428 --> 01:09:11,753
whether you're a game developer or you work in publishing or financing or your phone only

1065
01:09:11,793 --> 01:09:18,117
takes NFTs, whatever it is, what is about you is what you get up and put your energy

1066
01:09:18,157 --> 01:09:18,938
into every day.

1067
01:09:20,178 --> 01:09:20,839
And for me, I...

1068
01:09:22,665 --> 01:09:26,548
It has been such a gift to myself, to my co-workers and to my family

1069
01:09:27,148 --> 01:09:30,011
to get up every day with a little bit more of a mission,

1070
01:09:30,511 --> 01:09:32,173
something that matters to me, a purpose.

1071
01:09:32,793 --> 01:09:35,996
And that's what I wish for all of you as you go forth

1072
01:09:37,097 --> 01:09:43,322
in doing battle to create the most compelling entertainment in the history of people

1073
01:09:44,703 --> 01:09:48,806
that can also, we've learned, be quite beneficial for people,

1074
01:09:49,006 --> 01:09:51,308
both for those creating them and those playing them.

1075
01:09:52,535 --> 01:09:55,618
And so what we've done over the last 18 months is built a hive.

1076
01:09:56,399 --> 01:09:58,721
And it's up to the indie game developers of the world

1077
01:09:58,821 --> 01:09:59,702
to bring the honey.

1078
01:10:00,742 --> 01:10:04,205
Which is what right now, in this very moment,

1079
01:10:04,786 --> 01:10:07,028
we're announcing our first global game jam.

1080
01:10:07,048 --> 01:10:09,330
And in conjunction with global game jam.

1081
01:10:09,922 --> 01:10:13,046
where we are inviting indie developers around the world

1082
01:10:13,786 --> 01:10:17,090
to learn about what we're doing and to figure out how they can participate

1083
01:10:17,771 --> 01:10:20,113
in making games that are

1084
01:10:21,094 --> 01:10:25,178
scientifically beneficial for people, medically beneficial for people.

1085
01:10:26,360 --> 01:10:27,341
Should you so choose?

1086
01:10:28,765 --> 01:10:30,445
So I hope you'll accept our invitation.

1087
01:10:30,465 --> 01:10:32,546
I hope you'll learn about what we're doing

1088
01:10:32,606 --> 01:10:35,466
and realize the power that you as creators wield

1089
01:10:36,106 --> 01:10:38,707
and realize how you can change your own relationship

1090
01:10:38,747 --> 01:10:40,167
with the media that you take in.

1091
01:10:40,187 --> 01:10:42,708
Because anything we take in this much of,

1092
01:10:42,768 --> 01:10:46,529
whether it's food or water or air or media,

1093
01:10:46,949 --> 01:10:48,049
it has an effect on us.

1094
01:10:48,089 --> 01:10:49,369
It has a different effect on us

1095
01:10:49,429 --> 01:10:51,230
and it's different for each one of you.

1096
01:10:51,370 --> 01:10:53,430
So I invite you to look into that

1097
01:10:53,610 --> 01:10:54,891
and figure it out for yourselves.

1098
01:10:55,851 --> 01:10:56,911
My name is Mike Wilson.

1099
01:10:57,171 --> 01:10:58,172
Thank you all for your time.

1100
01:10:58,972 --> 01:10:59,592
I will see you soon.

1101
01:11:19,583 --> 01:11:20,463
There's a first for everything.

1102
01:11:21,583 --> 01:11:22,464
But that is a wrap.

1103
01:11:22,484 --> 01:11:25,484
I hope you all were as uplifted and informed as I was

1104
01:11:25,524 --> 01:11:26,705
by these transformative stories.

1105
01:11:26,785 --> 01:11:29,586
For more inspiration, join us back in this room tonight

1106
01:11:29,766 --> 01:11:31,426
for the IGF and Choice Awards

1107
01:11:31,466 --> 01:11:33,366
where we honour the best and brightest in games.

1108
01:11:33,927 --> 01:11:35,147
Doors open at 5.30pm.

1109
01:11:35,187 --> 01:11:36,507
I look forward to seeing you all here.

1110
01:11:36,907 --> 01:11:37,728
Have a great afternoon.

1111
01:11:37,748 --> 01:11:38,548
Bye!

